___
February 2nd marks the Feast Day of one of Yorubaland’s fiercest Orisa — OYA! 

“Oya represents the winds of change and transformation. Oya is owner and Queen of the marketplace. Oya is also the guardian of the cemetery and stands at the gate of the Ancestors — the door between life and death.  She is facilitator of transition. Oya, when danced, often has a horse tail. Her skirt and clothes have all the colors but black. Oya’s winds can be both a cool, gentle breeze and a fierce tornado. She is the “Mother of 9.” She is our female warrior self and gives us the tools we need to protect ourselves and families against forceful energy. She helps us to blow things out of our lives that are no longer needed.” 

— From ‘Spirit of the Orisa’ by @sulaspirit 
___
TRUE CONFESSION: I often tell people that when I first learned about the Orisa and started practicing Lucumi almost 20 years ago, I immediately identified with Oya. I said she is me! I reflected on my affinity for my Confirmation Saint — St. Joan of Arc. And identified with this fierce feminine warrior deity. Her relationship to Egun and the cemetery. Her willingness to ride into battle alongside Sango. I was enthralled! Of course, I was wrong about who would come claim my head. But at that time in my life, in my 20s, I truly leaned into the energy of personal transformation, using Oya as a guide. You don’t have to be initiated to tap into the universal lessons that these primordial beings come to teach. On this Oya’s day, I challenge you to consider what areas of your life are calling for a transformation. And to call on Oya to lead the way. But be mindful of what you ask for cause when Iya comes, she does not come to play. MAFEREFUN OYA! HECKUA HEY YANSA!
